Environmental deterioration has recently become the top worry for environmentalists. Ample resources, such as power and water, are needed for both home and industrial activities due to the continuously growing population and progress of the human race. The side products and leftovers of industrialization are released into the ambiance at the same time in the form of hazardous gases and effluents. Therefore, it is urgently necessary to control and regulate the toxins, particularly in the ambiance fluid. Nie et a. [67] presented the first instance of a paper-based sensor designed for the sensing of heavy metal in 2010. To move the sample through the device, they used screen-printed electrodes made from paper, on which microchannels were created using patterning methods. Mensah et al. [174] developed solid-contact ion-selective electrodes (SC-ISEs) based on a porous site to quantify Cd+2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
